 Fix & Redesign Column Feature Detection in Parametric Pipeline

 Context

 The parametric export pipeline detects feature edges (ridges, valleys) to create mesh edges that follow the actual surface geometry. Row sampling works correctly — it probes 8192 U-samples
  per T-row, detects gradient sign changes in cylindrical radius, and produces verified peaks/valleys. Column sampling is broken and currently disabled (LOCAL_ONLY_OUTER_ADAPTATION = true).
  When enabled, it generates horizontal lines around the outer wall surface.

 The goal is to redesign column detection so it can be re-enabled alongside row detection, producing a complete 2D feature map without artifacts.

 Root Cause Analysis

 Why column sampling produces horizontal lines

 Three interacting problems:

 1. Low T-resolution: Column detection extracts radius profiles from the already-probed row data. With ~100-300 T-rows, the T-direction profile has only ~100-300 samples vs 8192 in U. This
 makes detectColumnFeaturesV16() prone to spurious detections — gradient noise at low resolution produces false peaks.
 2. Fixed-U slicing of curved features: Each column samples at a fixed U position across all T-rows. If a ridge runs diagonally or curves through UV space, the fixed-U slice sees a
 distorted version of the feature — the column radius profile captures the intersection of a vertical UV line with the feature, not the feature itself. This creates spurious T-direction
 extrema that don't correspond to real surface features.
 3. Same-row clustering: When column detection adds features, the v16.1 snap-to-row logic finds the closest row for each T-feature. Multiple columns detecting spurious features at similar T
  heights snap to the same row, injecting a dense horizontal band of points — visible as horizontal lines in 3D.

 Semantic confusion in detectColumnFeaturesV16

 The function stores T positions in the FeaturePoint.u field (defined as "U position in [0, 1)"). While detectAndMergeColumnFeatures handles this correctly, it's a maintenance trap.

 The LOCAL_ONLY_OUTER_ADAPTATION workaround

 Column detection was disabled in v16.6 rather than fixed. This means:
 - No T-direction feature detection in the default pipeline
 - T-grid is strictly uniform — horizontal features have no representation
 - Styles with height-varying ridges get no special treatment in the T direction

 Proposed Fix: Dedicated GPU Column Probing

 The fundamental flaw is that column detection reuses row probe data (low T-resolution, fixed-U slicing). The fix mirrors the row probing architecture: GPU-probe dedicated T-direction
 strips at high resolution.

 Phase 1: GPU Column Probing (new dedicated T-strips)

 File: ParametricExportComputer.ts — Add a new GPU dispatch after row probing.

 Instead of extracting columns from row probe data, probe dedicated T-direction strips:
 - For each of COL_PROBE_COUNT (e.g., 64-128) evenly-spaced U positions:
   - Evaluate COL_PROBE_SAMPLES (e.g., 4096) T-values at that fixed U
   - This gives high-resolution T-direction radius profiles
 - Single GPU dispatch for all columns (same pattern as row probing)
 - Extract cylindrical radius from 3D positions

 This eliminates problems #1 (low resolution) and #2 (relies on already-probed row data).

 Phase 2: Rewrite detectColumnFeaturesV16 → detectTDirectionFeatures

 File: FeatureDetection.ts — New function with clean semantics.

 detectTDirectionFeatures(
     positions3D: Float32Array,  // High-res GPU probe data for one column
     numSamples: number,         // 4096
     minProminence: number
 ): { features: TDirectionFeature[]; rejected: number }

 - Input: 3D positions from GPU (not extracted row data)
 - Uses the same verified dual-strategy detection as detectRowFeaturesV16 (gradient sign changes + curvature shoulders)
 - Output type uses explicit t field (not overloaded u)
 - Non-periodic domain (T goes 0→1, no wrapping) — same as current detectColumnFeaturesV16 but at much higher resolution

 Phase 3: Cross-validate column features against row data

 File: FeatureDetection.ts — New function replacing detectAndMergeColumnFeatures.

 For each T-feature detected by the column probe:
 1. Find the two nearest T-rows that bracket this T position
 2. In those rows' 8192-sample U data, verify there's a matching radius extremum near the column's U position
 3. Only accept T-features that are corroborated by at least one neighboring row — this eliminates spurious detections from noise
 4. Use the row's verified U-peak position (not the column's grid U) for the final feature placement

 This eliminates problem #3 (same-row clustering of unverified features).

 Phase 4: Adaptive T-row insertion from verified column features

 File: ParametricExportComputer.ts — Re-enable T-feature merging in local-only mode.

 Instead of the removed CDF-adaptive spacing (which caused density bands), use a targeted approach:
 - Only insert extra T-rows at verified column feature positions
 - Maximum of N additional rows (configurable, e.g., 20) to prevent grid density explosion
 - Inserted rows go through the full row probing + feature detection pipeline
 - This preserves the uniform grid everywhere except at verified T-direction features

 Phase 5: Remove LOCAL_ONLY_OUTER_ADAPTATION flag

 Once column detection is reliable:
 - Remove the flag and its conditional branches
 - Column probing becomes a standard pipeline stage
 - T-feature row insertion is always-on (gated by detection quality, not a kill switch)

